  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2354590299" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2354590299" />
    <a title="sologdin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5610133-sologdin"><img alt="sologdin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1307928658p2/5610133.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2354590299?book_show_action=true">Sep 03, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="sologdin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="sologdin" href="/user/show/5610133-sologdin">sologdin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5610133-sologdin?shelf=of-best-sentence-and-moost-solaas">of-best-sentence-and-moost-solaas</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5610133-sologdin?shelf=law">law</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2354590299" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1663639909962790755">The author’s 1960 preface claims that “we think of ourselves in the third person,” “we no longer have, as past societies had, any picture of individual man […] by which to recognize ourselves and against which to measure ourselves; we are anything. But if anything, then nothing, and it is not everyone who can live with that” (xi), invoking plainly the ‘sheltering sky’ metaphors of Griffin’s work on fascism. Liberal society “finds no fixed points, but only the vaunted absence of them, ‘freedom’ a</span>
  <span id="freeText1663639909962790755" style="display:none">The author’s 1960 preface claims that “we think of ourselves in the third person,” “we no longer have, as past societies had, any picture of individual man […] by which to recognize ourselves and against which to measure ourselves; we are anything. But if anything, then nothing, and it is not everyone who can live with that” (xi), invoking plainly the ‘sheltering sky’ metaphors of Griffin’s work on fascism. Liberal society “finds no fixed points, but only the vaunted absence of them, ‘freedom’ and ‘opportunity’; freedom for what, opportunity to do what, is nowhere indicated” (id.). <br /> <br />His preface in some ways is an apology for his appropriation of a Catholic saint for secular purposes (xiii); in More’s time, “legal or illegal had no further meaning” (xvi), a kenomatic state of exception, likened to the present moment.<br /><br />More is presented as one who is as cool as it gets. When obsequious Rich is trying, for instance, to convince More, significantly, that “every man has his price” (4), More disregards it until Rich seems to define the price “in suffering,” by which is meant torture—but More says “for a moment I thought you were being profound” (5). He is of course somewhat conservative insofar as he warns his wife to avoid “dangerous leveling talk” (35), though his “beware of the Tower” suggests it is less conviction than accommodation to the Real. I, as an attorney, adore this presentation of More most as an attorney who says “I know what’s legal not what’s right” (65), one of the most famous scenes, wherein he’d “give the Devil benefit of law, for my own safety’s sake” (66). And of course it is difficult to avoid being smitten by More’s reading of the Act of Supremacy (83) or in his final arguments (149 ff), some of the finest dramatic writing out there. (His daughter’s solution to the central dilemma is Euripides’ from the <i>Hipppolytus</i>: “say the words of the oath and in your heart think otherwise” (140).) More himself channels Brecht by commenting on a hypothetical “happy land that needs no heroes” (140) (Brecht is cited in the preface, NB (xviii).)<br /><br />His ultimate adversary is Cromwell, who is the ‘government’ in Agamben’s sense from <i>The Kingdom and the Glory</i>, as opposed to the ‘sovereign’: “Oh they are the constitution. Our ancient, English constitution. I merely do things” (38). Cromwell is precisely agambenian in “the normal aim of administration is to keep steady this factor of convenience,” wherein “there are no rules” (73). (Henry VIII by contrast is presented as self-interested douche, less malevolent than trifling, reading scripture for his divorce and disputing with More, “Deuteronomy’s ambiguous!” (54), but then regarding More’s candid disagreement as “water in the desert” (55).)<br /><br />Recommended for those who pay their respects to the English Socrates as his angelic friend Erasmus calls him, numbnuts who’d labor like Thomas Aquinas over a rat-dog’s pedigree, and readers who first will disclaim their hearts and then will have no hearts.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1663639909962790755" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

